<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06304135 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06304135 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COLLEGE; BASKETBALL; ABUSE; REPORT; LAS-VEGAS  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Nevada-Las Vegas officials, using a video camera hidden in an air-conditioningduct, secretly taped a conditioning class during which basketball players mayhave been practicing early in violation of NCAA regulations.;   The schoolsaid Tuesday that it uncovered evidence that &quot;certain activities&quot; wereconducted in the class that might constitute basketball practice. It sent amemo to three assistant coaches asking them to appear at a hearing to answerthe allegations.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UNLV OFFICIALS MAKE SECRET TAPE OF PLAYERSAIR-CONDITIONING DUCT USED TO HIDE CAMERA  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  College Basketball; Notebook  </MEMO><TEXT>     One of the coaches, longtime assistant Tim Grgurich, expressed outragethrough his lawyer over the taping and claimed the university had also beenfollowing him and opening his mail.;   &quot;It's just another effort by theuniversity to destroy the basketball program,&quot; said Grgurich's lawyer, RoySmith. &quot;Where will they stop? Are they also bugging telephones?&quot;;   UNLV legalcounsel Brad Booke said the video camera was installed only after the schoolwas thwarted in efforts to dispel charges that UNLV players were practicingtogether before the official Oct. 15 start of practice.;   Booke declined tosay what was on the Oct. 8 videotape of the class, which has 13 UNLV playersamong its 28 students. The six-week conditioning class was a for-credit classopen to any UNLV student.;   He said the doors were locked to the campus gymwhere the class was conducted.;   &quot;Physical education classes are nottypically conducted behind closed doors,&quot; Booke said.; ETC.: The NCAA placedTexas-El Paso on three years' probation and limited its scholarships andcampus visits after uncovering several rules violations. The NCAA cut thenumber of school-paid visits by recruits to campus from 15 to eight. In1992-93 and 1993-94, the Miners can give only two new scholarships. UTEP wasnot banned from any postseason games.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911030  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  294  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, October 30, 199100304135,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>